SIMPLE: stickler
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Stickler
<hw>Stic"kler</hw> <pr>(st⟦icr⟧k"kl⟦etil⟧r)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>
<ety>[See <er>Stickle</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>]</ety> <def>One who
stickles.</def> Specifically: --⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(a)</sd> <def>One who arbitrates a duel; a sidesman to a fencer;
a second; an umpire.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Basilius, the judge, appointed <qex>sticklers</qex> and trumpets
whom the others should obey.</q> <rj><qau>Sir P. Sidney.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Our former chiefs, like <qex>sticklers</qex> of the war,⟦br⟧
First sought to inflame the parties, then to poise.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(b)</sd> <def>One who pertinaciously contends for some trifling
things, as a point of etiquette; an unreasonable, obstinate contender;
<as>as, a <ex>stickler</ex> for ceremony</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The Tory or High-church were the greatest <qex>sticklers</qex>
against the exorbitant proceedings of King James II.</q>
<rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stick-seed</ent>⟦br⟧
